My Dad loved watching birds, and after trial and error, he came up with his own solution. He used 1/2" or 3/4" electrical galvanized poles. Planted them into the ground away from trees or anything that an animal could potential jump from, usually in the middle of the yard. He then took some stove pipe and hardware cloth, wrapped the stove pipe around the pole about mid way up it and then put the hardware cloth in the middle and top of the stove pipe - usually preventing any animal (squirrels and raccoons) from being able to get to the bird and suit feeders.   It works really well, I still have some that I helped my Dad put up three years ago, using zip ties to attack brackets on to the pole and then the feeders onto the brackets. It's amazing how strong and durable zip ties are.
I really appreciate the effort put into this because I rescue baby squirrels!

Generating random paragraphs can be an excellent way for writers to get their creative flow going at the beginning of the day. The writer has no idea what topic the random paragraph will be about when it appears. This forces the writer to use creativity to complete one of three common writing challenges. The writer can use the paragraph as the first one of a short story and build upon it. A second option is to use the random paragraph somewhere in a short story they create. The third option is to have the random paragraph be the ending paragraph in a short story. No matter which of these challenges is undertaken, the writer is forced to use creativity to incorporate the paragraph into their writing.

Â @effoff1Â  Doesn't look like a jumper to me; I have kept jumping spiders for years. Yes, jumping spiders have a thing about 'butts in the air' (it's actually a courting thing) but they don't do it before they jump. As I said before, other spiders will throw out a line in the hopes of being picked up by the wind.  Jumping spiders will have their spinnerets to the ground before they jump, anchoring a drag line so that if the jump is unsuccessful, they can get back to the starting point. I have spent many hours watching them.  Jumper spiderlings do use the wind dispersal method but this definitely isn't a spiderling.

A feeder suspended from a very high branch with a long metal cable (think bicycle brake cable), under two overlapping cone-shaped or inverted bowl-shaped plastic or metal deflectors spaced a foot or two apart (so from top to bottom: cable, cone 1, 1-2 feet of cable, cone 2, feeder. They can hang on to the cable by their feet from above cone 1 but can't reach the feeder, and if they let go, they slide right off the cone. "Ten times less"? That's really sloppy and incorrect scientific terminology.  Something CANNOT be ten times less (or ANY times less). When you multiply (times) using whole numbers as you did, you ALWAYS  end up with a greater number. If you want a smaller number, you divide.   In other words, you can say that something "is ONE-TENTH (a number divided by ten) the amount of another thing", but you can't multiply whole numbers and get smaller numbers. It's impossible.

An astute observation. Their intelligence plus their adaptability is what has probably made them so successful a species. If you ever raise a foundling baby squirrel to adulthood, find that you and the squirrel have bonded to each other and decide to adopt the little guy to be a member of the family you will have a fabulous companion. But you must respect their right to be who they are. They are even more independent than cats and treated with proper respect, certainly more playful. They may live only about 10 years but for decades thereafter you will find nuts hidden all over the house. Like in sock drawers, in shoes, under a pile of sweaters, in shelves or drawers, down tub drains (fortunately, they float). There is a book by Bill Adler called Outwitting Squirrels. It claims to show 101 ways to outwit them. But if you had an idea that worked, you'd need only one, not 10I. I've read it and I think the subhead might read "Exercises in Hopeful Self-delusion." Given enough time, they'll devise workarounds against most any impediment between them and what they recognize to be necessities of life. They'll keep trying until they solve the problem. Intelligence plus a sound work ethic is a powerful combination.

It is impressive enough that the squirrels cleverly found ways around each obstacle. What may blow you away is the realization that the squirrels knew somehow that to get to the pile of walnuts at the end, they knew they had to start at a seemingly unrelated and distant first step and work forward, diligently solving nearly a dozen sequential puzzles as they approached the ultimate goal. That they connected the first step with the final one, started at the right point and persisted until they solved each subsequent step until the final goal was reached, is what I found most impressive. How old does a human child have to be before he or she attains the smarts to equal this achievement? I have raised numerous squirrels from babyhood, babies aimlessly wandering about or abandoned in the nest, scooped up by someone who brought the little guy to me. Smart dogs most often use their intelligence, I find, discovering what they can get away with. But squirrels are the only animals I needed to match wits with. Clever, determined little problem solvers, they showed an impressive work ethic and survival capability, manifested by a remarkable native intelligence. And they did it as a fun-loving smartass, sort of a cross between Bugs Bunny and Groucho Marx. One of the ones I raised figured out how to open a screw-top jar if there were nuts inside, but she tried to hide her ability from me until I held up the jar for her to work it open. Urban squirrels have trained us to supply them with nuts and in return they allow us to stand within their Radius of Cute while they munch away. That their rear feet swivel is why they can run down trees and vertical poles, while cats cannot. The lack of an opposable thumb may be all they lack to be a real threat to engineer employment. That they won over Mark Rober is not surprising. He recognized a clever fellow engineer when he saw one.

PS Mark ... squirrel-proof feeder that actually works:  take any circular birdfeeder, cut a metal circle about 50% larger (guessing) than the length of the feeder, bend it into a cone around the hanging implement (chain, etc).  When they try to reach the feeder, the cone tips down (and is slippery metal) past the end point of the feeder and they can't reach the feeder and slide off.  Hang it high enough that they can't jump on it from the ground.  Ours is hung from a tree.  We used metal from old car fender skirts.    I don't have the exact measurements correctly stated, that's up to you, the physics guy, to figure out.  All I know is that we made one and it's worked for years, they've never figured it out.  So now, they're content to clean up the overflow on the ground before the rats can get to it.  Thank you, squirrels!

just a suggestion; if you ever do this obstacle course again, you should put a one-way "door flap", like a cat door, on the front of each obstacle. They will then have to figure out how to lift the door up with their paw and duck under it in order to proceed. This way, they can't skip obstacles by jumping across. And for the obstacles without a top or sides to it, you could attach a piece of wood to the front of the obstacle with a cut-out for the door. And to ensure they don't just jump over that, you could essentially make a "false front"; use a piece of wood that makes the obstacle look too tall to jump over.  I also thought of some good obstacle ideas: - seesaw: a long narrow platform that is set up in such a way that it tilts one way or the other under load, similar to a seesaw. - slack line: what it says on the label. - Warp pipes: a squirrel-sized version of those tunnels that people use in hamster cages, but with a catch: there's three possible routes they could take. One actually leads to the other side. The second one leads to a vertical drop down to the ground. The third one loops on itself, effectively forming a dead end. alternatively, you could make three of the corridor maze obstacles where each one does the above; one leads through, one ends in a drop off, and the other is essentially a dead end. A decision-making obstacle.  - stepping stone bridge: follows the same principle as the ladder bridge, but it's a chain of platforms with a bit of rope between them. - cliffhanger: basically an upside-down rock wall. to get them started, you could have a sideways rock wall that leads up into the upside-down climbing wall. At the end, there's a platform they climb down to that's in front of the cat door entrance to the next obstacle, and to prevent the squirrels from jumping it, you could put a "anti-jump" partition on the front side, and make the climbing wall go around it.  - mine field: a grid of square platforms; some are static (do not move), some drop under load, and some wobble and tilt, similar to the seesaw one.

16:45 amazing.  In addition to using limbs to control rotation/orientation in space, aren't they using their tail even more to accomplish this?  Example: at 17:56, the entire body is rotating clockwise (relative to camera) along axis that goes through the length of the squirrel's body. Around 17:57, the squirrel's body has made half a rotation clockwise, but squirrel's tail begins to spin clockwise very rapidly. Effectively, the squirrel has transferred all/most of its angular momentum to its tail so that it's body stops rotating and stays in that orientation. That's really amazing.
Dear God....
nice

Conversely, if instead of stopping its body from rotating, a squirrel is not rotating in mid-air and wants its body to rotate, it rotates its tail in the opposite direction. E.g. if squirrel wants to rotate body counterclockwise, it will rotate its tail clockwise. Also, since the tail is lighter (in mass) than the body, the body will rotate more slowly than the tail. That's why the tail rotates so quickly in the footage - so that the body rotates at a decent rate.

I see a lot of comments about tails being used as helicopters, but I doubt the tail provides much lift (lift is what keeps aircraft up). More likely the tail is used to stabilize/fix the squirrel's orientation in space.  Example: at 17:56, the entire body is rotating clockwise (relative to camera) along axis that goes through the length of the squirrel's body. Around 17:57, the squirrel's body has made half a rotation clockwise, but squirrel's tail begins to spin clockwise very rapidly. Effectively, the squirrel has transferred all/most of its angular momentum to its tail so that it's body stops rotating and stays in that orientation. That's really amazing.

Alright, this is all highly entertaining, and I'm not here to be a buzzkill, but... It's bad engineering.  Good engineering follows Occam's Razor - the principle of parsimony - which states that the simplest answer is usually the right one.  In my case, keeping the squirrels out of the bird feeder took nothing more than hanging the feeder by a longer wire - a flattened coathanger works just fine.  In your preface you failed to lower the feeder out of the squirrels' stretching distance, and thus did not demonstrate that the simplest answer wouldn't work.  I get that doing so would have deprived you of all the woodwork and TV show references and fiddling with ardguidos and pneumatics, but dude, let's not pretend that all that stuff constitutes "good engineering".

I see a lot of comments about tails being used as helicopters, but I doubt the tail provides much lift (lift is what keeps aircraft up). More likely they are using their tail to stabilize/fix their orientation in space.  Example: at 17:56, the entire body is rotating clockwise (relative to camera) along axis that goes through the length of the squirrel's body. Around 17:57, the squirrel's body has made half a rotation clockwise, but squirrel's tail begins to spin clockwise very rapidly. Effectively, the squirrel has transferred all/most of its angular momentum to its tail so that it's body stops rotating and stays in that orientation. That's really amazing.

Very entertainig to watch! :D  Just a few things:  It was my first guess, that the squirrels will just jump over most of the obstacles to shortcut (and it looks like that's what they did). So the parcours needs a bit more of a jump protection. I'd have triggered the catapults the other way round: so they have to sit somewhere for a longer amount of time or be catapulted as soon as they try to sit on the next plate (sitting on it disables it for maybe 10 seconds). Because stepping over something is the normal behaviour. OR: Turn the catapult the other way round, that the 3 second trigger plate is somewhere where they have to pause to think about the next step, so they have to learn a larger chunk of the parcours first instead of using it step by step.  The diagonal plates haven't been slippery enough, they could just walk over it.  From a learning point of view there's a lot more experiments possible without harming these beautiful critters and still reward them greatly. And it looks like they really enjoyed their walnuts ;)   But that's all theorycraft, hoping there will be a version 2 some day ;) I wish I'd had a backyard with squirrels to play with. I see a lot of comments about tails being used as helicopters/propellers, but I doubt the tail provides much lift (lift is what keeps aircraft up). More likely they are using their tail to stabilize/fix their orientation in space.  Example: at 17:56, the entire body is rotating clockwise (relative to camera) along axis that goes through the length of the squirrel's body. Around 17:57, the squirrel's body has made half a rotation clockwise, but squirrel's tail begins to spin clockwise very rapidly. Effectively, the squirrel has transferred all/most of its angular momentum to its tail so that it's body stops rotating and stays in that orientation. That's really amazing.

Almost 50 years ago I solved the Squirrel in the Bird feeder.  I had a base or 24" X 30" with a sloping clear plastic roof.  I had Squirrels , Racoons, Posum, all competing  with the Birds.   The  that I drove into the groundfeeder was on a large Tree stump,  feeding all those critters got expensive.  I had a brilliant moment and put the feeder atop a 8 foot steel pipe, that I drove into the ground,  no problem for the Squirrels, every one else was left out.  Brilliant Idea 2  I greesed the top 3feet of the pole with vasalene,  The stuff you put, on your toddlers bum to prevent diaper rash,  Fun watching them get their paws in the V and try to get it off.  I had to grease up the pole every few days. But I had a big tub of V left over from when the boys were young.

However, how are you going to react when I say that you, yes you, good sir Mark, are but a product of a long-standing evolutionary experiment on behalf of mice squirrels, to develop smarter squirrels?  Daylight Robbery! (Jessica Holm, 1988) was a BBC documentary TV special (exported to America via PBS) that had exactly the same narrative arc. It started as an investigation to find a squirrel-proof bird feeder design -- witnessing feeder after feeder give up its treasures to the indomitable Sciuridae -- evolving to test the perseverance and intelligence of squirrels in an obstacle course, to end with not-so-grudging respect. Hilarious -- both documentaries! In fact, yours is so similar you must have seen it, right? Confess!  It seems that it is no longer able to be viewed online, but its 1991 sequel, Daylight Robbery 2, is on YouTube.

My grandfather cursed him for years until finally Bugsy never came back. Until he died in 2018 he would talk about how he missed that squirrel. I cherish those memories now and have all due respect to the evil genius of the squirrel kind.

Exactly! They are using their tail to stabilize/fix their orientation in space.  Example: at 17:56, the entire body is rotating clockwise (relative to camera) along axis that goes through the length of the squirrel's body. Around 17:57, the squirrel's body has made half a rotation clockwise, but squirrel's tail begins to spin clockwise very rapidly. Effectively, the squirrel has transferred all/most of its angular momentum to its tail so that it's body stops rotating and stays in that orientation. That's really amazing.

I see a lot of comments about tails being used as helicopters/propellers, but I doubt the tail provides much lift (lift is the force that keeps things in the air). More likely they are using their tail to stabilize/fix their orientation in space.  Example: at 17:56, the entire body is rotating clockwise (relative to camera) along axis that goes through the length of the squirrel's body. Around 17:57, the squirrel's body has made half a rotation clockwise, but squirrel's tail begins to spin clockwise very rapidly. Effectively, the squirrel has transferred all/most of its angular momentum to its tail so that it's body stops rotating and stays in that orientation. That's really amazing.

The little picnic table is basically my mum's solution to the squirrels and starlings - the sacrificial feeder. The good birdseed and mealworm mix goes in the cage she made around the feeder that's too small for squirrels or starlings to get through, and the walls too far apart to be reached through; the cheap fat feeders and peanuts are left in the open. Opportunists and lazy fuckers like them and pigeons will take the easy option and the bonus is that the more wary birds (usually coal tits) have learned that the cage is so secure that there's plenty of food for them and predators can't get in so they're safe to sit and eat to their hearts' content.

You might think that squirrels are cute, clever and incredibly athletic.  Sure, I agree with the clever and athletic part.  But otherwise I find them obnoxious pests--rodents with fuzzy tails, which they are.  They will chew through telephone lines or whatever gives them the equivalent of a trip to the rodentist.  So they're destructive little buggers.  They're also annoyingly stubborn, which is the flip side of persistence.  I had a nice little vegetable garden in my backyard, until a ground squirrel took up residence next to it, burrowing a home for himself under the fence about two feet from one side of the garden.  The garden plot was covered with a pvc-pipe and bird netting contraption to keep out birds and other pests, but of course that doesn't include squirrels that just chew through the bird netting and dig into the veggies.  I tried lots of discouragements to the squirrel--filling his burrow entrance, flooding the burrow, placing these supposed "repellant" powders around the garden, etc.  Nothing worked.  So finally I bought a trap, baited it with peanut butter and tried repeatedly to catch the squirrel.  After many tries, I caught him in the trap.  But I made a serious mistake after that, a mistake that I could have avoided if I did a little online research first about the homing ability of squirrels.  Being a compassionate animal lover, I released him about three miles from my house in a more rural area.  Next day, he was back at my house.  Turns out, squirrels have this amazing ability to find their way back to a previous preferred home.  That diminishes the farther away you take them--roughly five miles minimum, and preferably driving there on a twisting route, even if they're in the trunk of your car, as mine was.  As for how I finally rid myself of the little jerk, let's just say it was less pleasant for him.  But like Denzel Washington in "Equalizer," I gave him more than enough chances first.
